Objective¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

K Means Clustering¶

In [16]:
# Finding optimal no. of clusters
clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(df_z)
    prediction=model.predict(df_z)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df_z, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df
                           .shape[0])

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[16]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
In [17]:
# From the elbow plot above, we infer optimal clusters as 3 as this is the point where elbow of the plot curves.
# Hence, set the value of k=3
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, n_init = 15, random_state=12)
In [18]:
kmeans.fit(df_z)

Hierarchical Clustering¶

In [25]:
## Execute hierarchical clustering with different linkages and keep number of clusters as 3
model_average = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3, affinity='euclidean',  linkage='average')
model_ward = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3, affinity='euclidean', linkage='ward')
model_complete = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3, affinity='euclidean', linkage='complete')
model_single = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3, affinity='euclidean', linkage='single')
In [26]:
predict_hir_av = model_average.fit_predict(df_z)
predict_hir_wa = model_ward.fit_predict(df_z)
predict_hir_cm = model_complete.fit_predict(df_z)
predict_hir_si = model_single.fit_predict(df_z)
In [27]:
df_hir_av = df.copy()
df_hir_av_z = df_z.copy()
df_hir_av['Group'] = model_average.labels_
df_hir_av_z['Group'] = model_average.labels_

silhouette_avg_Hierarchial_av = silhouette_score(df_z,predict_hir_av,metric='euclidean')
tempResultsDf = pd.DataFrame({'Method':['Hierarchical clustering (Average)'], 'Silhouette Score': [silhouette_avg_Hierarchial_av]},index={'2'})
resultsDf = pd.concat([resultsDf, tempResultsDf])
resultsDf = resultsDf[['Method', 'Silhouette Score']]

# cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
# closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering

Z = linkage(df_z, metric='euclidean', method='average')
c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(df_z))

1. How many different segments of customers are there?¶

As we see above, we have three different segments of customers based on their average credit limit.

2. How are these segments different from each other?¶

These segments mainly differ based on credit limits as below.

1) High Credit Limit

2) Medium Credit Limit

3) Low Credit Limit

Customers who have high credit limit seems to be high spenders with more number of credit cards (mean value is around 9) and they prefer to bank online rather visiting the bank or calling bank

Customers who have low credit limit have less number of credit cards (which is understandable) and have more calls made to the bank

Customers with medium credit limit have more credit cards when compared to low credit customers and have less calls made to bank as compared to low credit customers but have more visits to bank overall

3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?¶

As we see there are three (3) categories/segments of customers with each segment having a preference for communication channel with bank, it is recommended that products are marketed to specific segment of customers through their preferred channel. Also, additional services can be provided based on how they connect with bank and also based on their spending pattern which can deduced from average credit limit.

  • Customers with high credit limit tend to vist online more for their needs. hence they can be targeted for online campaigns and accordingly products and services can be offered to them
  • Whereas customers with comparatively low credit limit make visits to bank more often, hence they can either be prompted with benefits of online banking or can be catered with in-bank offers/services and flyers
  • Similarly customers with low credit limits have less frequency on online platform, they can be marketed with benefits of online banking and/or make customer call center reps aware of promotions and offers so that they can target this segment of customers

Based on how bank wants to promote its products and services, a segment of customers can be targeted as we know their channel of preference.
